'''Oshisaka-nimasu Ikune Shrine''' (おしさかにますいくねじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in Sakurai City, Nara Prefecture. It is a Shikinaisha (Taisha), and its former shrine rank was village shrine.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* Sukunahikona-no-Kami

In sources such as the *Tokusen Shinmeichō* and the *Gōsonsha Torishirabechō* of Meiji 7 (1874), the enshrined deity is recorded as “Ikune-no-Kami.” However, details regarding this “Ikune-no-Kami” are unknown.

=== History ===
=== Overview ===
The date of establishment is unknown, but since the name appears as “Ikune Shrine households” in the *Yamato Province Shōzeichō* of Tenpyō 2 (730), and as “Ikune Shrine, one household, Yamato” in the *Shinshō Kyakuchokufu-shō* of Daidō 1 (806), it is believed to have been founded earlier than these records. In the *Engishiki Jinmyōchō*, it is listed as a Taisha and noted as receiving offerings at the Tsukinami and Niiname festivals. During the Edo period, it was simply called “Ikune Shrine,” and because there are also sacred rock formations (iwakura), it is believed that rituals were conducted at this site without relocation. In the past, there was also a shrine-temple (jingūji), the Ishii-dera Yakushi Hall, built in Genroku 2 (1689).

=== Divine rank ===
* January 27, Ten’an 3 (859): Promoted from Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade to Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade (as recorded in the *Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku*) — recorded under the name “Oshisaka Ikune Shrine.”

=== Precincts ===
There is no main hall at this shrine. To the north of the worship hall, 21 natural stones known as “Ishigami” are arranged and venerated as the sacred object in the form of an iwakura.

=== Access ===
* Approximately 1 km south from Yamato-Asakura Station on the Kintetsu Osaka Line

